<DOC><DOCNO> AP890327-0135 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 2010EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Immigration     03-27 0186</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Immigration,0193</SECOND><HEAD>Japan Turns Away, Deports Record Number Of Foreigners</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Japan last year turned away or deported 17,854foreigners for carrying fake passports or working illegally,according to a Justice Ministry report Monday.   For the first time in 10 years, the number of males deported forviolating immigration law exceeded that of females and was 90percent higher than in 1987, the report said. The number of womendeported fell by 16 percent, the report said.   Of the total, more than 16,000 foreigners overstayed visas and14,300 of these were employed without proper working papers, thereport said.   The remaining foreigners were turned away at borders with fakepapers, the report said.   The largest national group deported was from the Philippines,followed by illegal workers from Bangladesh, Pakistan and SouthKorea, the report said.   In the last three years, people from developing Asian nationshave flocked to Japan, where they usually find illegal work onconstruction sites, in restaurants or in small factories, a JusticeMinistry official said. They earn far more than they would in theirown countries, the official said.</TEXT></DOC>